    <segment id="1" parent="14" relname="span">Intuitiveness is a term that concerns the features of the interactive system that allow novice users to understand how to use it and then how to attain a maximal level of performance.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="3" relname="antithesis"> 
It is well known that people donÂ’t like to spend a long time learning how to use a system.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="16" relname="span"> 
They want to get started straight away and become competent carrying out tasks without too much effort.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="circumstance"> 
This is especially true an interactive products intended for everyday use.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="15" relname="span"> 
In case for more complex systems (e.g., Word processors, web-authoring tools, etc.) that provide a wider range of functionality, users are willing to spend longer time learning these products.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="17" relname="span"> 
With the presence of online tutorials and CD-Rom can help by providing interactive step-by-step materials with hands-on exercises.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="otherwise"> 
Some users might find it difficult to relate to the tasks they want to accomplish.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="20" relname="span"> 
An important concern is to determine the time the user spend on learning a system.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="12" relname="span"> 
There seems a little point in developing a range of functionality in a product </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="13" relname="span">
if the majority of users are unable or not prepared to spend time learning how to use it.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="11" relname="nonvolitional-result"> 
So interactive product designers should keep in mind while developing such a product to keep the level of ease with which new users can begin effective interaction and achieve maximal performance.</segment>
